  • lots of things in the database that can be visualised
  • one aspect I'm interested in particular is the sharing when a campaign starts
  • how the data is logged enables us to trace how the movement is being spread
  • the left three columns show the share links, their corresponding users and the time of creation
  • but we can also find out how these links get created
  • (for example) User 2 clicks on link A shared by user 1, and link B is created in turn …
  • we can actually connect the dots and understand how the movement is being spread not only over time but also over the network
  • similar to spreading a virus and creating an epidemic
  • there are statistical models readily avaiable for real-life epidemics, we just need to modify them a bit for the network

Statistical modelling

A few parameters to explain a relationship or phenomenon
  • have to explain when statistical modelling actually does because people seem so scared about it
  • a mathematically elegant way of explaining a relationship or phenomenom
  • by calculating the curvature of the smooth red line, you can summarise the relationship between cost and revenue and also predict what a future revenue looks like with a given cost
  • technical details - sth I have to worry about
  • might oversimplify things - but "all models are wrong; some are useful"
  • what's important is that we provide a useful description of the data with a few parameters
  • in fact there are models that can capture the essence of more complex process, and epidemic models are one of them

Susceptible-Infectious model

One parameter needed: the epidemic rate
  • one of these is called the susceptible-infectious model, where you start with one person being infectious, and infects anybody that comes into contact with that person
  • those infected become infectious and will infect others who are still susceptible
  • this is plotting the cumulative count of the infected and susceptible over time
  • for app movement, we can define anybody who hasn't seen the campaign page as susceptible. Once they click the link shared by others on the social network, they become infected.
  • in this way, this graph is telling the same story as this table
  • all you need to create this epidemic is the constant rate of contacting other people
  • if any of you knows about epidemiology, this is actually related to the basic reproduction number

Homogeneous mixing epidemic

Everyone is connected to everyone else
  • as I said before, we can look at the epidemic spreading not only over time, but also over the network
  • black lines represent that two people are connected and so there is a potential infectious contact, while red lines represent the actual infections
  • assume everyone has the potential to infect anyone else
  • makes sense if the epidemic takes place in e.g. a classroom or an office, but possibly not on a social network because not everybody is connected

Network epidemic

Everyone has the same average number of connections
  • a quick fix is that any two people have the same probability of being connected to each other
  • each person has the same number of connections on average
  • doesn't describe a real-life network well
  • as we can see in previous slides, there are people at the periphery of the network, while some are hubs in the central of the network

Real-life networks

Some are much more connected than others - the hubs
  • this looks more like a real-life network, where 1 and 2 have a lot more connections than others
  • this is the kind of network that gives rise to, for example, six degrees of separation, because things can travel fast in this network via the hubs
  • now we can use the epidemic rate to spread the campaign, we need to construct the network itself first

Preferential attachment

Start with one connection
  • it turns out there is a simple but powerful model that can generates this kind of network; this model is called preferential attachment
  • you start with one connection, and

Preferential attachment

Newcomers sequentially connect to those already in the network
  • others will join the network one by one and connect to those already in the network

Preferential attachment

Current connectedness affects how likely one gets connected to a newcomer
  • the one rule of selecting whom to connect is that the more connected you are, the more likely you will get connected to the newcomer.
  • this creates the effect that the rich gets richer, and …

Preferential attachment

The rich gets richer
  • … eventually you will have the network we've seen
  • you can see those coming late are only having one or two connections, but if you are early in the network, you are much more likely to become the hubs.
  • there is only one magic number required to create this preferential attachment network, and that is the average number of new connections. …

Spreading the epidemic

The epidemic rate kicks in
  • together with the other magic number, which is the epidemic rate, we have successfully recreated the data.
  • when it comes to actual data analysis, we have to estimate these two parameters, but that's not the hard bit.

The actual data

Most connections are unknown
  • in the actual data, we only have the information about the infections, so we have to discover the unknown connections as well, on top of estimating the two parameters.

Discovering the unknown connections

  • Analyse multiple epidemics simultaneously
  • Compare their epidemic rates
  • luckily, in the app movement data we have multiple epidemics taking place in a shared universe, which is open lab, so we can pull their information together and do the analysis on several epidemics in one go.
  • we may also compare their epidemic rates and explain the differences in
  • this is something I will leave to another time, but I hope this talk gives you an idea that it is possible to analyse such data with statistical models.
